STREPTOCOCCUS, GROUP A, SCARLET FEVER - CANADA: (PRINCE EDWARD ISLAND) REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
**********************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 21 Jan 2014
Source: The Guardian [edited]
http://www.theguardian.pe.ca/News/Local/2014-01-21/article-3584675/Scarlet-fever-making-rounds-in-Prince-Edward-Island/1


Scarlet fever seems to be making the rounds in the province [Prince Edward Island (PEI), Canada] but Health PEI does not track the numbers because it is related to strep throat, which is easily treated with antibiotics. But don't panic, it's not as scary as it sounds.

The illness is actually a manifestation of a strep [streptococcal] infection. Parents have reported to The Guardian that an official with the new 811 telehealth line has told them anecdotally that scarlet fever is going around in PEI.

Dr Lamont Sweet, PEI's deputy chief public health officer, said Monday [20 Jan 2014] the strep infection only manifests as scarlet fever when it is the 1st time a person has contracted the illness. "Scarlet fever is your 1st attack of strep throat," he said. "Usually it has a red rash, a fever, swollen glands in the neck, and then the tongue is usually involved with either a white coating or raised bumps in which case it can be quite red and they call it a strawberry tongue." The red, or scarlet, rash is caused by a substance released into the blood from bacteria from the infection.

The good news is, after you've had this rash once, your body becomes immune to it in future. So, if you contract strep throat again, it will not be accompanied by the scarlet rash.

The Health Department does not track cases of strep throat in PEI, as it is a common illness that is easily treated with antibiotics. The reason it has a bad reputation is because strep throat, or scarlet fever, used to be accompanied by rheumatic fever. "Strep has changed in that we almost never hear of rheumatic fever," Sweet said. "No one really knows too much about why this happened. Fortunately the strep has been less likely to cause trouble . . . we've just not been getting the major complications that we used to get."

[Byline: Teresa Wright]

